#*#*#*#*#*#*#*#*#*#*#*#*#*#*#*#*#*#*#*#*#*#*#*#*#*#*#*#*#*#*#*#*#*#*#*#
        Propositional calculus
#*#*#*#*#*#*#*#*#*#*#*#*#*#*#*#*#*#*#*#*#*#*#*#*#*#*#*#*#*#*#*#*#*#*#*#
$)

$(
Informally, propositional calculus can be thought of as describing formulas
that are universally "true" when their variables are replaced by any
combination of "true" and "false".  Such formulas are called "tautologies".  In
standard texts, there is a metatheorem that allows tautologies to be proved
very simply using truth tables.  However, this metatheorem is too advanced from
our minimalist perspective, as it implicitly presupposes set theory.  We
therefore derive everything we need directly from the axioms.
$)

  $( Declare the primitive constant symbols for propositional calculus. $)
  $c ( $.  $( Left parenthesis $)
  $c ) $.  $( Right parenthesis $)
  $c -> $. $( Right arrow (read:  'implies') $)
  $c -. $. $( Right handle (read:  'not') $)
  $c wff $. $( Well-formed formula symbol (read:  'the following symbol
               sequence is a wff') $)
  $c |- $. $( Turnstyle (read:  'the following symbol sequence is provable' or
              'a proof exists for') $)

  $( Introduce some variable names we will use to represent well-formed
     formulas (wff's).  Traditionally, Greek letters are used as metavariables
     ranging over wff's. $)
  $v ph $. $( Greek phi $)
  $v ps $.  $( Greek psi $)
  $v ch $.  $( Greek chi $)
  $v th $.  $( Greek theta $)
  $v ta $.  $( Greek tau $)

  $(
     Specify some variables that we will use to represent wff's.
     The fact that a variable represents a wff is relevant only to a theorem
     referring to that variable, so we may use $f hypotheses.  The symbol
     ` wff ` specifies that the variable that follows it represents a wff.
  $)

  $( Let variable ` ph ` be a wff. $)
  wph   $f wff ph $.
  $( Let variable ` ps ` be a wff. $)
  wps   $f wff ps $.
  $( Let variable ` ch ` be a wff. $)
  wch   $f wff ch $.
  $( Let variable ` th ` be a wff. $)
  wth   $f wff th $.
  $( Let variable ` ta ` be a wff. $)
  wta   $f wff ta $.

  $(
     Recursively define wff's.  Note that we only define wff's built up
     from other wff's, i.e. there is no starting or "atomic" wff.  Later,
     in predicate calculus, we will extend the basic wff definition by
     defining atomic wff's.
  $)

  $( If ` ph ` is a wff, so is ` -. ph `.  Part of the recursive definition
     of a wff. $)
  wn $a wff -. ph $.

  $( If ` ph ` and ` ps ` are wff's, so is ` ( ph -> ps ) `.  Part of the
     recursive definition of a wff.  $)
  wi $a wff ( ph -> ps ) $.

$(
=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=
        The axioms of propositional calculus
=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=
$)

  $(
     Postulate the three axioms of classical propositional calculus.  See,
     for example, Definition 2.1, p. 28, of Hamilton.
  $)

  $( Axiom of Simplification.
     One of the 3 axioms of propositional calculus. $)
  ax-1 $a |- ( ph -> ( ps -> ph ) ) $.

  $( Axiom of Distribution.
     One of the 3 axioms of propositional calculus. $)
  ax-2 $a |- ( ( ph -> ( ps -> ch ) ) -> ( ( ph -> ps ) -> ( ph -> ch ) ) ) $.

  $( Axiom of Contraposition.
     One of the 3 axioms of propositional calculus. $)
  ax-3 $a |- ( ( -. ph -> -. ps ) -> ( ps -> ph ) ) $.

  $(
     Postulate the modus ponens rule of inference.
  $)

  ${
    $( Major premise for modus ponens. $)
    maj   $e |- ( ph -> ps ) $.
    $( Minor premise for modus ponens. $)
    min   $e |- ph $.
    $( Rule of Modus Ponens.
       The postulated inference rule of propositional calculus. $)
    ax-mp $a |- ps $.
  $}

  $(
     ~ax-1 , ~ax-2 , ~ax-3 , and ~ax-mp are the complete set of
     postulates for propositional calculus.  Some additional $a statements
     are used later to introduce defined terms.
  $)

$(
=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=
        Logical implication
=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=
$)

$( The results in this section make use of the first 2 axioms only.  In
   an implication, the wff before the arrow is called the 'antecedent'
   and the wff after the arrow is called the 'consequent.' $)

$( We will use the following descriptive terms very loosely:  A 'theorem'
   usually has no $e hypotheses.  An 'inference' has one or more $e hypotheses.
   A 'deduction' is an inference in which the hypotheses and the result
   share the same antecedent. $)

  ${
    $( Premise for ~a1i . $)
    a1i.1 $e |- ph $.
    $( Inference derived from axiom ~ax-1 . $)
    a1i   $p |- ( ps -> ph ) $=
      ( wi ax-1 ax-mp ) ABADABECF $.
  $}

  ${
    $( Premise for ~a2i . $)
    a2i.1 $e |- ( ph -> ( ps -> ch ) ) $.
    $( Inference derived from axiom ~ax-2 . $)
    a2i   $p |- ( ( ph -> ps ) -> ( ph -> ch ) ) $=
      ( wi ax-2 ax-mp ) ABCEEABEACEEABCFDG $.
  $}

  $( Principle of identity.  Theorem *2.08 of Whitehead and Russell. $)
  id $p |- ( ph -> ph ) $=
      ( wi ax-1 a2i ax-mp ) AAABZBFAFAAFCDAACE $.

  $( Principle of identity.  Theorem *2.08 of Whitehead and Russell.  This
     version is proved directly from the axioms for demonstration purposes. $)
  id1 $p |- ( ph -> ph ) $=
      ( wi ax-2 ax-1 ax-mp ) AAABZBZFAFABBGFBAFACAFDEAADE $.

  $( Principle of identity with antecedent. $)
  idd $p |- ( ph -> ( ps -> ps ) ) $=
      ( wi id a1i ) BBCABDE $.
      $([26-Nov-95]$)

  ${
    $( First of 2 premises for ~syl . $)
    syl.1  $e |- ( ph -> ps ) $.
    $( First of 2 premises for ~syl . $)
    syl.2  $e |- ( ps -> ch ) $.
    $( Syllogism inference. $)
    syl    $p |- ( ph -> ch ) $=
      ( wi a1i a2i ax-mp ) ABFACFABCBCFAEGHDI $.
  $}

  ${
    $( Premise for ~comm . $)
    comm.1 $e |- ( ph -> ( ps -> ch ) ) $.
    $( Inference that swaps (commutes) antecedents in an implication. $)
    comm   $p |- ( ps -> ( ph -> ch ) ) $=
      ( wi ax-1 a2i syl ) BABEACEBAFABCDGH $.
  $}

  ${
    a1d.1 $e |- ( ph -> ps ) $.
    $( Deduction introducing an embedded antecedent. $)
    a1d   $p |- ( ph -> ( ch -> ps ) ) $=
      ( wi a1i comm ) CABABECDFG $.
  $}

  ${
    a2d.1 $e |- ( ph -> ( ps -> ( ch -> th ) ) ) $.
    $( Deduction distributing an embedded antecedent. $)
    a2d   $p |- ( ph -> ( ( ps -> ch ) -> ( ps -> th ) ) ) $=
      ( wi ax-2 syl ) ABCDFFBCFBDFFEBCDGH $.
      $([23-Jun-94]$)
  $}

  $( A closed form of syllogism.  Theorem *2.05 of Whitehead and Russell. $)
  syl1 $p |- ( ( ph -> ps ) -> ( ( ch -> ph ) -> ( ch -> ps ) ) ) $=
      ( wi ax-1 a2d ) ABDZCABGCEF $.

  $( A closed form of syllogism.  Theorem *2.06 of Whitehead and Russell. $)
  syl2 $p |- ( ( ph -> ps ) -> ( ( ps -> ch ) -> ( ph -> ch ) ) ) $=
      ( wi syl1 comm ) BCDABDACDBCAEF $.

  ${
    $( Premise for ~syl3 . $)
    syl3.1 $e |- ( ph -> ps ) $.
    $( Inference adding common antecedents in an implication. $)
    syl3   $p |- ( ( ch -> ph ) -> ( ch -> ps ) ) $=
      ( wi a1i a2i ) CABABECDFG $.
  $}

  ${
    syl4.1 $e |- ( ph -> ps ) $.
    $( Inference adding common consequents in an implication, thereby
       interchanging the original antecedent and consequent. $)
    syl4   $p |- ( ( ps -> ch ) -> ( ph -> ch ) ) $=
      ( wi syl2 ax-mp ) ABEBCEACEEABCFDG $.
  $}

  ${
    syl34.1 $e |- ( ph -> ps ) $.
    syl34.2 $e |- ( ch -> th ) $.
    $( Inference joining two implications. $)
    syl34   $p |- ( ( ps -> ch ) -> ( ph -> th ) ) $=
      ( wi syl3 syl4 syl ) BCGBDGADGCDBFHABDEIJ $.
  $}

  ${
    3syl.1 $e |- ( ph -> ps ) $.
    3syl.2 $e |- ( ps -> ch ) $.
    3syl.3 $e |- ( ch -> th ) $.
    $( Inference chaining two syllogisms. $)
    3syl   $p |- ( ph -> th ) $=
      ( syl ) ACDABCEFHGH $.
  $}

  ${
    syl5.1 $e |- ( ph -> ( ps -> ch ) ) $.
    syl5.2 $e |- ( th -> ps ) $.
    $( A syllogism rule of inference.  The second premise is used to replace
       the second antecedent of the first premise. $)
