  $(
  A (complex) number is a class (set), and the decimal representation of a
  number is effectively a class constant symbol.  Decimal numbers are defined
  recursively in terms of digit strings (with an optional decimal point).
  The recursive definition can be "unwound" to determine the actual formula
  for the class the digit string represents.  Each digit is a separate
  Metamath token.  If individual digits were allowed to represent classes
  there would be ambiguity in the representation of decimal numbers, since
  three adjacent class symbols in parentheses represent the result of an
  operation.  Thus we wouldn't know whether (1 2 3 4) means (12 3 4) or (1 23
  4) or (1 2 34) (of course it is meaningless to use numbers as operators but
  formally any class symbol can be used as an operator).  To prevent
  ambiguity we do not allow isolated digits or digit strings;
  instead we suffix all digit strings with the ASCII token _10 to designate
  the end of a digit string.

  Digit strings will usually be unambigous without whitespace (for better
  readability) although we will separate digits, at least initially in our
  development, to emphasize that they are separate Metamath tokens.
  $)

  $( Class of complex numbers. $)
  cc $a class CC $.
  $( Class of real numbers. $)
  cr $a class RR $.
  $( Extend class notation to include the complex number 0.  Note that
     the subscript ` _10 `, meaning base 10, indicates the end of a digit
     string to eliminate ambiguity. $)
  cn0 $a class 0 _10 $.
  $( Extend class notation to include the complex number 1. $)
  cn1 $a class 1 _10 $.
  $( Extend class notation to include the complex number i. $)
  cni $a class i $.
  $( Addition on complex numbers. $)
  caddc $a class + $.
  $( Multiplication on complex numbers.  The token ` x. ` is a center dot. $)
  cmulc $a class x. $.
  $( Less than predicate (defined over real subset of complex numbers). $)
  clt $a class < $.

  $( Define the class of complex numbers. $)
  df-c $a |- CC = ( N_r X. N_r ) $.

  $( Define the complex number 0 (base 10). $)
  df-0 $a |- 0 _10 = <. 0_r , 0_r >. $.

  $( Define the complex number 1 (base 10). $)
  df-1 $a |- 1 _10 = <. 1_r , 0_r >. $.

  $( Define the complex (imaginary) number i. $)
  df-i $a |- i = <. 0_r , 1_r >. $.

  ${
    $d x y $.
    $( Define the class of real numbers. $)
    df-r $a |- RR = ( N_r X. { 0_r } ) $.
